      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw construct model. QoI (stiffness, yield force) changed by <1.5% between the medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation-based GCI was 3.1%, satisfying the acceptance criterion. The production mesh corresponds to the medium-density level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force and displacement residuals converge to <1e-4 relative tolerance; energy balance error <0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solution convergence was monitored across all load steps. Force residuals converged to 8.3e-5 and displacement residuals to 6.1e-5 relative tolerance. Energy balance error was 0.04%. No divergence events were observed across the simulation ensemble."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts by a second qualified analyst.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed all model setup files, boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and post-processing scripts against the simulation plan. Two minor discrepancies in constraint application were identified and corrected prior to production runs. Final configuration was re-reviewed and approved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity is appropriate for metallic implant compression-bending; contact mechanics formulation validated against published literature.",
      "rationale": "The model employs continuum solid elements with bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (Ti-6Al-4V ELI, ASTM F136). Augmented Lagrangian contact formulation is used at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. This model form is consistent with published FDA guidance and peer-reviewed literature for metallic spinal implant simulation. The referenced methodology publication (doi:10.1016/j.ymeth.2024.03.003) describes the validation framework applied here."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports (MTRs) for each lot; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E = 113.8 GPa, yield = 827 MPa, UTS = 896 MPa) were obtained from certified MTRs for the Ti-6Al-4V ELI rod and screw stock used in testing. Geometric dimensions were verified by CMM measurement of three representative specimens per lot. Variability in material properties across lots was within 2% and was propagated through a sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative lots; traceability to device history records confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5). All specimens were manufactured from production-representative lots with full traceability to device history records. Dimensional inspection confirmed conformance to drawing tolerances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration at a fixed load offset. While this configuration is the regulatory standard, it represents only one point in the clinical loading space. Achieved level (2) is below the required level (3) for this factor; this gap is noted as a limitation of the current validation scope and is accepted given the regulatory precedent for F1717 as the standard test method."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions, load application, and fixture geometry replicate F1717 test setup geometry to within measurement uncertainty; confirmed by overlay of CAD fixture model with test photographs.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model boundary conditions were defined to replicate the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry. CAD models of the test fixtures were obtained from the laboratories and incorporated into the simulation. Overlay comparison with test photographs confirmed geometric fidelity. Load application point and direction were verified against the test machine crosshead displacement records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs; graphical overlay of force-displacement curves.",
      "rationale": "Three primary QoIs were compared: construct stiffness (E/uval = 0.84), yield force (E/uval = 1.12), and force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval = 1.61). All three satisfy E/uval < 1.96. Force-displacement curve overlays show good agreement throughout the elastic and early plastic regimes. Experimental uncertainty was quantified per ASME V&V 40 Section 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) directly correspond to regulatory submission requirements and clinical performance indicators for spinal fixation constructs.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs selected (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the standard outputs required by FDA for ASTM F1717 regulatory submissions and directly reflect clinically relevant construct performance. Stiffness relates to load sharing with the spine; yield force indicates onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm represents post-yield structural integrity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
